description.text:
A Remix of the Rostock Carriage Igus/Traxxas mod. I modified it for several reasons:
  • fit my universal endstop-holder ( http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:471761 )
  • i dont like these "grid-style" belt mountings. they break of easily and doesn’t provide a nice fit; 2 screws with a clip-holder makes more sense to me.
  • front belt-mount; some designs like "zam kossel alt" require this, but there are not many Rostock front-belt designs out there.
    • the endstop-screw is - looking on the top - moved closer to the center between the smooth rods and not far in front of like in most other designs. on some rostock designs this is easier to mount, especially, when you have to front-mount your belts. i also slightly enlarged the hex-nut holes. when they are to tight, the material tends to break when tightening the screws. the clamp should prevent the belts from putting to much force to the carriage and loosening it. It is not just a desing feature, if the belt is tighten properly, it WILL pull the screws outwards a bit and loosening itself, even with washers and if screwed tight!
printed with .5 nozzle, .3 layer height and 25% infill @60mm/s

title: Lossless Rigidbot E3D V6 mount - 40mm Fan Option

description.text:
This is my latest version, which uses the stock 40mm fan for more airflow and easier-to-find replacements. Work in progress because I have not had time to test it extensively but the basic premise of the design is the same as my other one, which has been holding up well.   
This design does not require the plate to be trimmed, however you will require 2x M3 x 25mm and 2x M3 x ~10mm screws, available at any hobby shop or many places online.

Use at your own risk - I am not responsible for any injury or damage, etc. Print in ABS, use supports and 100% infill. Finish by drilling out the 3mm holes, which are intentionally sized a bit small to accommodate variations in tolerances. File a notch into the plastic part that mounts to the extruder. You will see where you have to file when you go to test fit - just file where the top of the e3d would hit the plastic. I decided this was better than spacing the motor up higher than necessary.
Finally, cut the PTFE tube at an angle so it fits close to the hobbed bolt and won't let soft filament go anywhere but where it's supposed to. Enjoy!

title: Pet water feeder. READ instructions carefully.

description.text:
Our host site has carefully concealed the cup feeder part over on the other side, thingiview rotate to unhide.
Make sure to see the instructions tab or else your print will be a 2kg door stop! There is some minor post processing to do.
This creation is a storage container with holes only at the bottom.
Fill it with water, using a tube from your tap if necessary and then gently tip it pointy side up and place for your pets to drink from. I will be doing a version of this using less plastic, but I like the aesthetics of it.
Probably best to print in clear PLA and leave out of the direct sun else your pet will get warm water and evaporation may push some water out.

I made a very robust print using two outside layers of 0.8 nozzle diameter setting, The nozzle setting should be greater than your actual nozzle orifice diameter for maximum adhesion! Don't worry, your slicing program will adapt and make the tracks further apart.
4 top layers and 4 bottom layers. There cannot be any leaks or it won't work. Use a layer height of 0.25
DON'T USE ANY FILL!!
The main component is created as a solid, this allows you to have very good control over thickness because you can specify number of layers and the printer won't dawdle with small fills and retraction moves. The cup part sticking out from the base is set as a thick shell to ensure shape and printing. If you try to do a mini of this, keep an eye on your wall thickness for the cup part and ensure it's thicker than your nozzle diameter setting. Check that the cup is forming correctly before leaving it unattended.
Make sure vase setting is OFF or it may override your top layer setting and make a hole on top like my one. I simply got some spare PLA scrap layers, heat gun melted the surface and joined it to the top. Then I clipped around the sides, heated the messy bits and smoothed them into the main body.
You will have to manually melt, dremmel or drill out a couple of holes of about 8mm diameter inside the cup into the main storage body of the feeder to allow water to be piped into it. if drilling, use a blunt drill bit so it doesn't catch. Dremmeling or melting is safest though!
Once filled up, simply rock it forwards. Mine doesn't leak any water after filling while rotating to upright. Because the water rises to cover the holes, no air can get in and atmospheric air pressure keeps the water balanced inside.
If you get any leaking of water, check the holes are under the level of the cup! (Duh)
You can fill any obvious defects by running your extruder on very slow manually, any invisible defects, spray coat with polyurethane to wick in to any voids, dry and retry.

title: Paddle grip array for club print, sized from small to large fists.

description.text:
Printed in an array of finely tuned fist size differences to suit Pixie to Troll sized fists. Tape or heat shrink to your paddle shaft with the finger spacers in line with the back surface of the wing paddle. This will help to keep your hands in the correct place, reduce fatigue and help you to keep the paddle at the correct angle all the time so you don't fall in. :)  
I used 1.5 x actual nozzle diameter in my settings to force fat fast trails, 3 perimeters with 0 distance(brim), 3 top and 4 bottom layers. 190C PLA at hot end, 55C heated glass. 30mm extrude/sec, 0.25mm layer height. No Fill !  
Small wisps of filament help to keep the array of grips from falling over during the build.  
After build, separate, clean up the ends and fix to your paddle shaft. Using a heat gun on low and gripping around as it cools will help to tidy it and customise it to your hand shape.

title: Building Jig for 4x4x4 RGB LED cube

description.text:
I needed a tool to help making a 4x4x4 cube of RGB LEDs. So I built this thing. There are notches on the top of each LED holder for the R,G,and B leads, the anode points straight up.
You can build this with an unmodified Printrbot simple Maker model 1405.
Now, you have a former for the LEDs. You will find 3 small holes that go all the way through.
  • Push the 3 RGB leads into the holes as far as they will go the anode goes to the outside.
  • Fold the LED at a right angle.
  • Pull the LED up till the edge of the LED is even with the top of the former.
  • Push the LED up right again,
    Now the LED and it leads should look like the ones in the picture.
    Finally there is a 16-hole plate so once you have made 16 columns, you can arrange the columns for the final solder.
    • Here is a photo gallery of a build:
    https://plus.google.com/photos/+JonProietti/albums/6069528284601631137

To use,
  • Place the jig on a solid surface with the last block(the one with the shelf) to your right (see the picture).
  • insert one led in each of the holder blocks, with the longest(anode) as the second furthest from you.
  • Bend all 4 legs up as close to the base of the LED as possible.
  • Now bend the RGB leads so they lay in the cut-outs in the next block to the right. The last led will not have a block just approximate it as close as you can.
  • Solder the leads, left to right. You may need to move the LED out of the socket a little to compensate for the first lead or the one nearest you being almost too short.
    !!!DONOT SOLDER THE ANODE!! This is the toughest part, you need to keep the anode away from the leads on either side as you solder.
    More instructions will be provided once I finish the second part of the JIG.

This is a minor modification of Johann's Kossel extruder, which makes it parametric allowing to fit different spur gears or pulleys, moreover, if required, it adds a mounting bracket.  
Do not download the STL file, most probably it will not fit your requirements, donwload instead the OpenSCAD file to generate your STL.

This remix makes possible to use different spur gears or pulleys. So it is possible to generate the original Johann's extruder, as much, by changing few easy parameters, to adapt it to fit different pulleys with different diameters. It is also possible to specify the diameter of the screw of the pneumatic fit. One extra feature is the ability to choose if the extruder needs to be printed with an additional mounting bracket.
The OpenSCAD file allows modifications to the following parameters:
new_rad is the radius of the pulley / spur gear
pn_rad is the radius of the pneumatic fit screw
pi_rad is the extra radius for the pulley / spur gear indent
pi_h is the height of the pulley / spur gear indent
hmount is to enable (1) or disable (0) the mounting bracket
Once you modify these parameters you will have a ready extruder to fit your gears.

description.text:
A while ago I broke the lid of my beloved teapot (it's been in the family for over two decades). So I made a new one with my Prusa.  
This was an opportunity to try a fun new workflow. The lid has radial symmetry (its group is O(2) for the mathematically inclined), making it a good job for OpenSCAD's rotate_extrude.  
To get the appropriate outline to extrude I used Inkscape, tracing by eye with the aid of a photo.  
The Inkscape to OpenSCAD extension did the rest of the heavy lifting.  
I added some support material for the lid's "lip" and knob; this should detach easily. One of the challenging aspects was cutting a small notch in the knob support in OpenSCAD, as there is no support for partial rotate_extrude built-in.
I also customize these rings with letters on the faces - works for names of six letters or less !

Our avatar will travel on the network because the technology has found a way to involve the five senses in the experience of virtual navigation.
An Italian entertainer says: "In 2040, the pizza will be downloaded online!"

The electric motor is powered by hydrogen fuel cells as the difficult problem of hydrogen storage has been resolved.
A handful of solar cells will help the engine.
I have therefore developed the concept of independent suspension by means of articulated arms.
In a real model can be operated with servo motors so as to compensate shaking and orienting the body to counteract the centrifugal force when cornering.
Waiting for someone to solve these problems,
I focused on the possibility to simulate the behavior of the suspension at least on this small scale model.
I also raised the issue of the wheels without hub.
The front wheels rotate on a spherical seat and on the cylindrical surface of the large annular support. The model can really run!
The rear axle protrudes from the differential and rigidly supports the two drive wheels placed very close to the differential, without the need for drive shafts articulated transmission, with constant velocity joints. The entire subgroup rotates on a support arm so as to adapt to the ground (see the screenshots)
The two rear arms and the front ones are grafted on a pin that protrudes from the body, in the middle of this pin an elastic element absorbs the shocks of the two arms.
It is a simple leaf spring molded with an elastic material.
To calibrate the stiffness of the spring and right size would be needed to make proofs,
as it happens I could really use anMakerBot Replicator 2!

This figure called Bad Elf is a very good and ambitious fighter.
He has three arms, one with a sword, the second one for grabbing and the third one for the crossbow.
Further advantages of the Bad Elf are that he is able to fly and with the four legs he stands solid on the ground.
Have a lot of fun with my Bad Elf!!!
